pshire and Surrey): from Middle English <i>crate</i> ‘hurdle, basket’, or occasionally perhaps from <i>crete</i> ‘cradle’, probably applied as a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such articles. Alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Croft   1."]},{"name":"Crofts","meanings":["English: variant of   Croft  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Groft","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Croft  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne Croft was born in 1340, in Harrington, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Ralph Croft, was 27 and her mother, Maude Harrington, was 22. She had at least 1 son with John Copledike. She died after 1355."},"et":{"1340–after 1355":"1340–pärast 1355","1340–1355":"1340–1355","1338–1381":"1338–1381","1360–1408":"1360–1408","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1318–Female":"1318–Surnud","1338":"1338","1314":"1314","1355":"1355","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1408":"1408","1381":"1381","after 1355":"pärast 1355","Abt 1339":"umbes 1339","1318":"1318","Harrington, , Lincolnshire, England":"Harrington, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Harrington, Lincolnshire, England":"Harrington, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1340–after 1355":"1340–1355 jälkeen","1340–1355":